
[1]impotency

   IM'POTENCY, n. [L. impotentia; in and potentia, from possum. See
   Power.]

   1. Want of strength or power, animal or intellectual; weakness;
   feebleness; inability; imbecility; defect of power, natural or
   adventitious, to perform any thing.

   Some were poor by the impotency of nature; as young fatherless
   children, old decrepit persons, idiots and cripples.

   The impotence of exercising animal motion attends fevers.

   2. Moral inability; the want of power or inclination to resist

                or overcome habits and natural propensities.

   3. Inability to beget.

   4. Ungovernable passion; a Latin signification. [Little used.]
